R3 fingerprint: `<!-- agent-fp: 7287d3880d98 -->`.

## Trigger scenario

1. A course or event is published; `enqueueEmbedOnPublish()` runs, sets `EmbeddingSync.status = "pending"`, and enqueues an EMBED job.
2. The BullMQ worker processes the job and calls OpenAI successfully — the job moves to the `completed` state.
3. BullMQ's `removeOnComplete: {count: 50}` housekeeping cleans up the job's Redis key. With moderate publish volume (>50 jobs completing in quick succession), this eviction happens before the `QueueEvents` pub/sub `completed` event is fully dispatched.
4. `setupAiResultHandler()` receives the `completed` event and immediately calls `getAiQueue().getJob(jobId)`.
5. `getJob()` returns `null` — the job record no longer exists in Redis.
6. The handler logs `ai.result.job_not_found` at warn level and returns. `handleEmbedResult()` is never called.
7. `content_embeddings` is never written or updated. `EmbeddingSync` remains `status = "pending"` with no error.

The cron batch eventually retries (up to 2 minutes later), burning a second OpenAI call. Under sustained load where the cron queue itself is deep, this delay can extend further.

## Root cause

`ai-result.handler.ts` calls `getAiQueue().getJob(jobId)` in the `completed` event handler solely to retrieve `job.data.kind` (the job type discriminator). The `returnvalue` payload passed by BullMQ to the `completed` event already contains the full `EmbedResult` (including `embedding`, `entityType`, `entityId`, `locale`). The extra `getJob()` round-trip is unnecessary and introduces the race: by the time the async pub/sub event reaches the Next.js process, BullMQ's automatic cleanup may have already evicted the job key from Redis.

## Fix sketch

Remove the `getJob()` call entirely. Infer the job kind by type-narrowing on the `returnvalue` shape already present in the event:

```typescript
queueEvents.on("completed", async ({jobId, returnvalue}) => {
  try {
    const result = typeof returnvalue === "string" ? JSON.parse(returnvalue) : returnvalue;
    if ("embedding" in result) {
      // Kind = EMBED — all fields needed are in result
      await handleEmbedResult({jobId, result});
    } else if ("text" in result) {
      // Kind = GENERATE
      // ... existing observe call ...
    } else {
      observe("ai.result.no_handler", {jobId}, {level: "warn"});
    }
  } catch (error) { /* ... */ }
});
```

This eliminates both the Redis round-trip and the race window, and also makes the `Queue` singleton in `ai-result.handler.ts` redundant (can be removed, closing the duplicate-connection issue noted by the performance review).

Related prior issues: none (first occurrence in this area).
Verified by: performance-engineer (primary), qa-tester, workflow-orchestrator (parallel scan 2026-05-24).

