R3 fingerprint: `<!-- agent-fp: 2e044db85786 -->`.

**File:** `apps/experts-app/app/api/v1/internal/storage-janitor/orphan-sweep/route.ts`

## Vulnerability

The `POST /api/v1/internal/storage-janitor/orphan-sweep` route uses the identical timing-unsafe authentication pattern as [EXP-112](https://linear.app/experts/issue/EXP-112/security-cron-secret-timing-unsafe-comparison-and-fail-open-on-storage) (`storage-janitor/sweep/route.ts`):

```typescript
export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  const authHeader = request.headers.get("authorization");
  const cronSecret = process.env.CRON_SECRET;

  if (!cronSecret || authHeader !== `Bearer ${cronSecret}`) {
    // plain !== : timing oracle — short-circuits at first differing byte
    const {authorized, error: authError} = await requireAdmin();
    // fail-open: any admin session bypasses CRON_SECRET entirely
    if (!authorized) {
      return NextResponse.json({error: authError || "Forbidden"}, {status: ...});
    }
  }
  const result = await runOrphanAttachmentSweep();
  ...
}
```

Two distinct issues:

1. **Timing oracle:** Plain `!==` comparison short-circuits at the first differing byte, enabling a network attacker with many requests to recover `CRON_SECRET` byte-by-byte via response-time measurement.
2. **Fail-open to admin:** When `CRON_SECRET` is absent or wrong, any `requireAdmin`-passing session can invoke `runOrphanAttachmentSweep` on demand.

## Amplified impact post-PR #493 ([EXP-121](https://linear.app/experts/issue/EXP-121/bug-storage-reservation-ledger-never-decrements-used-bytes-on-file) fix)

`runOrphanAttachmentSweep` now calls `releaseStorageBytes()` after each deletion (merged 2026-05-26). An admin who triggers this sweep out-of-schedule can:

* Prematurely delete attachment records and R2 objects that have not yet reached the 24h grace window
* Decrement `user_storage_usage.used_bytes` for those users, freeing quota that should still be counted

This is the same class as [EXP-112](https://linear.app/experts/issue/EXP-112/security-cron-secret-timing-unsafe-comparison-and-fail-open-on-storage) but covers a **separate route** that was not included in the [EXP-111](https://linear.app/experts/issue/EXP-111/bug-storage-pending-reaper-and-storage-orphan-reaper-cron-routes-use) fix scope (PR #478 fixed `storage-pending-reaper` and `storage-orphan-reaper` routes, not `storage-janitor/orphan-sweep`).

## Attack paths

**Path 1 — timing oracle (network attacker):**
Attacker → Authorization header iterated byte-by-byte → timing delta on `!==` comparison → CRON_SECRET recovered → full bypass.

**Path 2 — admin fail-open:**
Admin user → POST `/api/v1/internal/storage-janitor/orphan-sweep` without valid CRON_SECRET → `requireAdmin` succeeds → `runOrphanAttachmentSweep` fires → files within the 24h grace window deleted + `used_bytes` decremented for affected users.

**Impact:** Premature deletion of user files (data loss for attachments < 24h old) + quota under-counting (effective quota widening) for all affected users.

## Remediation

Replace the auth block with the pattern used in `reservation-cleanup/route.ts` and `storage-alerts/check/route.ts`:

```typescript
const cronSecret = process.env.CRON_SECRET;
if (!cronSecret) {
  console.error("[orphan-sweep] CRON_SECRET is not set — refusing all requests");
  return NextResponse.json({error: "Service misconfigured"}, {status: 500});
}
const authHeader = request.headers.get("authorization") ?? "";
const expected = `Bearer ${cronSecret}`;
const a = Buffer.from(authHeader);
const b = Buffer.from(expected);
const authorized = a.length === b.length && crypto.timingSafeEqual(a, b);
if (!authorized) {
  return NextResponse.json({error: "Forbidden"}, {status: 403});
}
```

Remove the `requireAdmin` fallback entirely — destructive cron endpoints must not have an authenticated-user bypass.

