## Severity

**Medium**

## Location

`apps/experts-app/app/api/v1/internal/realtime/sync/route.ts` — `GET` handler, `viewingPostIds` extraction block (\~lines 156–170, introduced in the existing codebase, no auth guard added in 2026-05-28 safeErrorJson sweep commit `842d6baa2d71`)

## Description

The `GET /api/v1/internal/realtime/sync` endpoint accepts a `channels` query parameter containing comma-separated channel names. Channel names matching `post:POST_ID:events` are extracted as `viewingPostIds` and included directly in Prisma activity queries **without any authorization check on whether the requesting user can access the specified post**:

```ts
// From user-supplied channels param — no ownership check
const viewingPostIds = new Set<string>();
requestedChannels.forEach((channel) => {
  const postMatch = channel.match(/^post:(.+):events$/);
  if (postMatch) {
    viewingPostIds.add(postMatch[1]); // Any post ID accepted
  }
});

const postIds = Array.from(
  new Set([...userPosts.map((p) => p.id), ...Array.from(viewingPostIds)]),
);

// Activities (like_added, like_removed, reaction_changed) queried for ALL postIds
// including unowned ones from viewingPostIds
const likeActivities = await prisma.activity.findMany({
  where: {
    entityId: { in: commentIds }, // commentIds includes comments on arbitrary postIds
    ...
  },
  ...
});

// Emitted to client with actor's userId
events.push({
  type: eventType,
  payload: {
    userId: activity.userId, // reveals who interacted
    ...
  },
  ...
});
```

The route has no auth guard (no 401 returned when unauthenticated; `userId` is simply set to `null`). Both authenticated and unauthenticated users can subscribe to any post's activity stream.

## Attacker → Input → Reach → Impact

* **Attacker**: Any user — authenticated or unauthenticated (no session required)
* **Input**: `GET /api/v1/internal/realtime/sync?channels=post:PRIVATE_POST_ID:events`
* **Reach**: Public internet; no credentials required; can be polled continuously since there is no rate limiting visible
* **Impact**: (1) Real-time activity feed (likes, unlikes, reaction changes) on any post — including private posts — is exposed to anyone who knows or can enumerate the post ID. (2) The `userId` of every actor (who liked/commented on the private post) is included in the response, leaking the social graph of private post interactions. (3) Combined with incremental polling, an attacker can build a timeline of all interactions on any post over time.

Note: The route also issues an unbounded `prisma.comment.findMany` for all comments in `viewingPostIds` (no `take:` limit), which compounds the IDOR by enabling enumeration of all comment IDs on targeted posts.

## Recommended Remediation

1. **Authorization check**: Before including user-supplied post IDs in `viewingPostIds`, verify the requesting user has read access to each post (e.g., `prisma.post.findFirst({ where: { id: postId, OR: [{ isPublic: true }, { userId }] } })`). Reject or silently ignore unauthorized IDs.
2. **Require authentication**: Return 401 if `session?.user?.id` is null (the route currently proceeds silently with no user context).
3. **Rate limiting**: Add rate limiting to the polling endpoint to prevent enumeration attacks.
4. **Limit unbounded query**: Add `take: 500` or similar limit to the `allCommentsInPosts` `findMany` call.

Related prior issues: none

