## Summary

In `app/api/v1/courses/[id]/reject/route.ts`, `request.json()` is called before the `try` block and before auth is checked. A body parse error from an unauthenticated request is not caught by the route error handler. Same class as [EXP-210](https://linear.app/experts/issue/EXP-210/spinoff-exp-199-publish-route-parses-request-body-before-auth-guard) (publish route body-before-auth).

## File

`apps/experts-app/app/api/v1/courses/[id]/reject/route.ts` — `POST`

## Root Cause

```ts
export async function POST(request: NextRequest, ...) {
  const {id} = await params;
  const session = await auth();
  const body = await request.json().catch(() => ({}));  // ← OUTSIDE try block, before auth gate
  try {
    if (!session?.user?.id) {
      return NextResponse.json({error: "Unauthorized"}, {status: 401});
    }
    // ...
  } catch (error: unknown) {
    return safeErrorJson(error, {...});
  }
}
```

## Trigger Scenario

1. Send `POST /api/v1/courses/{id}/reject` with a malformed body from an unauthenticated session.
2. `request.json()` throws before auth runs; `.catch(() => ({}))` currently swallows it silently.
3. Unauthenticated callers cause the server to buffer and parse the full request body before any auth gate fires.
4. If `.catch` is removed in a future refactor or a different error surfaces, it propagates outside the error handler.

Related: [EXP-210](https://linear.app/experts/issue/EXP-210/spinoff-exp-199-publish-route-parses-request-body-before-auth-guard) (publish route, same pattern).

## Fix

Move `await request.json()` inside the `try` block, after the `session?.user?.id` check.

